80 to 120 proof, made from sorghum and sometimes other grains depending on the region. as the word "ji«î" is often loosely translated as "wine" by chinese beverage firms and english speakers, baijiu is frequently referred to as "white wine" in conversation. baijiu will typically be served at banquets and festivals in tiny shot glasses. toasts are ubiquitous at banquets or dinners on special occasions. most foreigners find baijiu tastes like diesel fuel, while a liquor connoisseur may find high quality, expensive baijiu quite good. baijiu is definitely an acquired taste, but once the taste is acquired, it's quite fun 